  <Properties>
    <articleContributors>
      <Value><![CDATA[<p class="p1">Alexandre Marcio Marcolino, Rafael In&aacute;cio Barbosa, Lais Mara Siqueira das Neves, Nilton Mazzer, Rinaldo Roberto de Jesus Guirro, Marisa de C&aacute;ssia Registro Fonseca</p>]]></Value>
    </articleContributors>
    <articleCopy>
      <Value><![CDATA[<p class="p1">Peripheral nerve lesions caused sensory and motor deficits along the distribution of the injured nerve. Numerous researches have been carried out to enhance and/or accelerate the recovery of such lesions. The objective of this study was to assess the functional recovery of sciatic nerve in rats subjected to different fluences of low-level laser therapy (LLLT). Thirty-six animals were randomly divided into four groups: one consisting of sham rats and three others irradiated with progressive fluencies of 10 J/cm2, 40 J/cm2 and 80 J/cm2 of laser AsGaAl (830 nm) for 21 consecutive days. They were evaluated by the Sciatic Functional Index (SFI) method. The crush injury was performed by using a portable device with dead weight of 5,000 g whose load was applied for 10 min. A digital camera was used to record the footprints left on the acrylic track, before surgery and after, on the 7th, 14th, and 21st days. The results also showed that on the 7th day, there was a difference between the groups irradiated with 40 J/cm2, when compared with the sham group (p &lt; 0.05). On the 14th day the groups irradiated with 40 J/cm2 and 80 J/cm2 also presented better results when compared with sham, however, on the 21st day, no inter-group difference was found (p &gt; 0.05). It was possible to observe that the LLLT at fluency of 40 J/cm2 and 80 J/cm2 had a positive influence on the acceleration of the functional nerve recovery.</p>]]></Value>
    </articleCopy>
